{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"language":"python","display_name":"Python 3","name":"python3"},"language_info":{"name":"python","version":"3.12.12","mimetype":"text/x-python","codemirror_mode":{"name":"ipython","version":3},"pygments_lexer":"ipython3","nbconvert_exporter":"python","file_extension":".py"},"kaggle":{"accelerator":"none","dataSources":[{"sourceType":"datasetVersion","sourceId":16336524,"datasetId":10472452,"databundleVersionId":17326184}],"dockerImageVersionId":31328,"isInternetEnabled":true,"language":"python","sourceType":"notebook","isGpuEnabled":false}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"source":"<a href=\"https://www.kaggle.com/code/rabbani0123/spatial-temporal-analysis-of-pm2-5-dynamics-15-30?scriptVersionId=321134758\" target=\"_blank\"><img align=\"left\" alt=\"Kaggle\" title=\"Open in Kaggle\" src=\"https://kaggle.com/static/images/open-in-kaggle.svg\"></a>","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown"},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Spatial-Temporal Dynamics of Pakistan's Air Quality (2015–2030)\n\n**Prepared by:** Mohammad Rabbani | **Domain:** Environmental Analytics & Public Health Risk Assessment  \n\n---\n\n### Executive Abstract\nThis notebook provides a rigorous spatial-temporal evaluation of urban air quality across Pakistan using a localized 11-year panel dataset (110 total observations across 10 major urban centers). Moving beyond aggregate national averages, this analysis tracks historical metrics to evaluate three core atmospheric phenomena:\n\n1. **Spatial Disparity:** The geographical concentration of particulate matter within the Punjab Smog Belt.\n2. **Seasonal Multipliers:** The compounding impact of the winter thermal inversion effect on baseline pollution.\n3. **Regulatory Non-Compliance:** Evaluation of urban exposure against the World Health Organization (WHO) safety guidelines.\n\nFinally, we implement an Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) Linear Regression framework to project ambient $PM_{2.5}$ trends for key industrial hubs through the year 2030.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"import pandas as pd\nimport numpy as np\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\nimport seaborn as sns\nfrom sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression\n\n# Environment settings for clean, publication-grade visuals\nsns.set_theme(style=\"whitegrid\")\nplt.rcParams.update({\n    'font.size': 11,\n    'axes.labelsize': 12,\n    'axes.titlesize': 14,\n    'xtick.labelsize': 11,\n    'ytick.labelsize': 11,\n    'figure.titlesize': 16\n})\n\n# Load the localized panel data (REPLACE THE PATH BELOW)\nfile_path = '/kaggle/input/datasets/rabbani0123/pakistan-air-quality-annual-summary-2015-2025/pakistan_air_quality_annual_summary.csv'\ndf = pd.read_csv(file_path)\n\n# Quick validation of dataset structural integrity\nprint(f\"Dataset successfully initialized. Total Records: {df.shape[0]}, Total Features: {df.shape[1]}\")\ndisplay(df.head())","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 1. Geographic Polarization: The Punjab Smog Belt\n\nAir pollution profiles across Pakistan are heavily influenced by local geography, industrial density, and transboundary meteorology. By filtering our data to the most recent comprehensive cross-section (2025), we can map the stark spatial disparities that exist between provinces. \n\nWe define the strict World Health Organization safe annual exposure threshold ($5.0 \\ \\mu g/m^3$) as our scientific baseline.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Filter and sort the cross-sectional data for 2025\ndf_2025 = df[df['year'] == 2025].sort_values(by='pm25_annual_avg', ascending=False)\n\nplt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))\n\n# Highlight Punjab cities dynamically to expose the geographic cluster\ncolors = ['#C0392B' if x == 'Punjab' else '#34495E' for x in df_2025['province']]\nbars = plt.bar(df_2025['city'], df_2025['pm25_annual_avg'], color=colors, edgecolor='black', alpha=0.85)\n\n# Add the WHO guideline reference anchor\nplt.axhline(y=5.0, color='#2980B9', linestyle='--', linewidth=2, label=r'WHO Safe Annual Threshold ($5.0 \\ \\mu g/m^3$)')\n\n# Annotate values directly on top of bars for immediate analytical clarity\nfor bar in bars:\n    height = bar.get_height()\n    plt.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width()/2., height + 2, f'{height:.1f}', ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=10, fontweight='bold')\n\nplt.title('Urban Spatial Disparity: Annual Average PM2.5 Concentrations (2025)', pad=15, fontweight='bold')\nplt.ylabel(r'Annual Mean $PM_{2.5}$ Concentration ($\\mu g/m^3$)')\nplt.xlabel('Urban Sampling Center')\nplt.xticks(rotation=30)\nplt.legend(frameon=True, facecolor='white')\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 2. Atmospheric Compounding: The Winter Inversion Multiplier\n\nEvaluating annual mean values alone can cloud the short-term physiological dangers faced by urban populations. During late autumn and winter, colder ground temperatures compress the atmospheric boundary layer, trapping vehicular and industrial emissions close to the surface. \n\nTo visualize this transition from summer baseline lows to peak winter spikes, we construct a descriptive dumbbell plot mapping the minimum monthly average directly against the peak winter monthly average for each city.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Sort cities by their peak exposure levels to preserve layout hierarchy\ncity_seasonal = df[df['year'] == 2025].sort_values(by='pm25_peak_month', ascending=True)\n\nplt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))\ny_range = range(1, len(city_seasonal) + 1)\n\n# Generate structural link lines between data points\nplt.hlines(y=y_range, xmin=city_seasonal['pm25_min_month'], xmax=city_seasonal['pm25_peak_month'], \n           color='#BDC3C7', linestyle='-', linewidth=2.5, alpha=0.6)\n\n# Plot scatter distributions representing the seasonal shift\nplt.scatter(city_seasonal['pm25_min_month'], y_range, color='#2ECC71', s=100, label='Annual Minimum Month Exposure', zorder=3, edgecolor='black')\nplt.scatter(city_seasonal['pm25_peak_month'], y_range, color='#E74C3C', s=100, label='Peak Winter Inversion Exposure', zorder=3, edgecolor='black')\n\nplt.yticks(y_range, city_seasonal['city'])\nplt.xlabel(r'Particulate Concentration Thresholds ($\\mu g/m^3$)')\nplt.title('The Winter Inversion Effect: Seasonal Multipliers Across Urban Centers (2025)', pad=15, fontweight='bold')\nplt.legend(loc='lower right', frameon=True)\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 3. Historical Trajectories & Predictive Modeling (To 2030)\n\nTo assess whether existing localized atmospheric conditions are improving, deteriorating, or stabilizing, we isolate four distinct sentinel hubs representing different populations and baseline pollution loads:\n* **Faisalabad & Lahore:** Core industrial/agricultural zones in the Punjab Smog Belt.\n* **Karachi:** Coastal megacity benefiting from maritime air clearing.\n* **Islamabad:** Northern capital characterized by localized green spaces and alternative topography.\n\nWe train an Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) Linear Regression model on the 2015–2025 historical series to project the ambient linear trend line up to 2030.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"plt.figure(figsize=(13, 7))\n\nsentinel_cities = ['Faisalabad', 'Lahore', 'Karachi', 'Islamabad']\nfuture_years = np.array(range(2026, 2031)).reshape(-1, 1)\npalette = {'Faisalabad': '#7D6608', 'Lahore': '#78281F', 'Karachi': '#1B4F72', 'Islamabad': '#145A32'}\n\nfor city in sentinel_cities:\n    city_data = df[df['city'] == city].sort_values('year')\n    X_hist = city_data['year'].values.reshape(-1, 1)\n    y_hist = city_data['pm25_annual_avg'].values\n    \n    # Render underlying historical data points\n    line = plt.plot(city_data['year'], y_hist, marker='o', linewidth=2, color=palette[city], label=f'{city} (Observed History)')\n    \n    # Train the OLS Linear Regression Model\n    model = LinearRegression().fit(X_hist, y_hist)\n    y_pred = model.predict(future_years)\n    \n    # Render forecast trajectory lines\n    plt.plot(range(2026, 2031), y_pred, linestyle=':', linewidth=2.5, color=palette[city], alpha=0.85, label=f'{city} (2026-2030 Trend Projection)')\n\n# Add absolute critical threshold comparison line\nplt.axhline(y=5.0, color='#C0392B', linestyle='--', linewidth=1.5, label='WHO Target Baseline Limit (5.0 µg/m³)')\n\nplt.title(r'Empirical $PM_{2.5}$ Historical Trends & Linear Regression Projections (To 2030)', pad=15, fontweight='bold')\nplt.xlabel('Calendar Year Target')\nplt.ylabel(r'Annual Mean $PM_{2.5}$ Concentration ($\\mu g/m^3$)')\nplt.xlim(2015, 2030)\nplt.xticks(range(2015, 2031, 2))\nplt.legend(loc='upper right', bbox_to_anchor=(1.35, 1.0), frameon=True)\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"---\n### References & Methodological Notes\n1. **World Health Organization (WHO) Guidelines:** The baseline threshold of $5.0 \\ \\mu g/m^3$ utilized in this analysis reflects the updated 2021 WHO Global Air Quality Guidelines (AQGs) for long-term ambient particulate matter exposure.\n2. **Predictive Constraints:** The Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) regression utilized for the 2026-2030 projections assumes a linear continuation of localized industrial, agricultural, and meteorological patterns. It does not account for sudden, unannounced macroscopic policy interventions.","metadata":{}}]}